⭐ PantheonOS — Universal File Schema v1.0

The Single Canonical Format for All Artifact Ingestion

PantheonOS does not reason over files.
It reasons over Artifacts, which are structured, geometric, audited entities.

This schema defines the only permitted representation for external data entering PantheonOS via MIIL.

1. Top-Level Structure

{
  "ArtifactID": "string",
  "Fingerprint": {
    "ByteHash": "string",
    "GeometryHash": "string",
    "SemanticHash": "string",
    "CompositeHash": "string"
  },
  "Metadata": {
    "OriginalName": "string",
    "OriginalType": "string",
    "ByteSize": "number",
    "ReceivedAt": "timestamp",
    "Source": "string"
  },
  "Geometry": {
    "Type": "string",
    "Structure": {},
    "Invariants": {}
  },
  "Semantics": {
    "HoneyNodes": [],
    "NoveltyScore": "number",
    "DomainLinks": []
  },
  "Doctrine": {
    "Routes": [],
    "Confidence": "number",
    "FrameDeltaContribution": {}
  },
  "Audit": {
    "Verifier": "string",
    "Timestamp": "timestamp",
    "KernelSignature": "string"
  }
}


⸻

⭐ 2. Field Breakdown

2.1 ArtifactID

A UUIDv7 (time-sortable) representing the artifact within PantheonOS.

⸻

⭐ 2.2 Fingerprint Object

PantheonOS uses four fingerprints, not one:

✔ ByteHash
	•	SHA-256 of the raw bytes
	•	Identifies the literal artifact (never stored permanently)

✔ GeometryHash
	•	SHA-256 of serialized Geometry.Structure
	•	Ensures geometric integrity
	•	Two different files can converge to the same geometry

✔ SemanticHash
	•	SHA-256 of the Honey bundle
	•	Used to track conceptual identity

✔ CompositeHash
	•	SHA-256(ByteHash + GeometryHash + SemanticHash)
	•	Pantheon’s canonical ArtifactFingerprint
	•	Passed into the Sovereign Kernel

⸻

⭐ 2.3 Metadata Block

Tracks provenance and context.

{
  "OriginalName": "example.pdf",
  "OriginalType": "pdf",
  "ByteSize": 19432,
  "ReceivedAt": "2025-11-30T18:44:00Z",
  "Source": "user-upload"
}

Pantheon never needs the content again — only these properties.

⸻

⭐ 2.4 Geometry Block

This is where the Spider + Hypatia work becomes structured.

Fields:

✔ Type

One of:
	•	"text-manifold"
	•	"pixel-field"
	•	"spectrogram-tensor"
	•	"table-graph"
	•	"frame-tensor"
	•	"syntax-tree"
	•	"directory-graph"
	•	"json-graph"
	•	"binary-block"

✔ Structure

A type-specific, lossless-but-safe geometric representation:
	•	token arrays
	•	adjacency lists
	•	tensor shapes
	•	parse trees
	•	frame timelines

✔ Invariants

Geometry-derived invariants:
	•	edge counts
	•	component sizes
	•	eigenvalues
	•	layer signatures
	•	dominant frequencies

These ensure reproducibility, compression, and identity.

⸻

⭐ 2.5 Semantics Block

Output from Bee + Dragonfly.

Fields:

✔ HoneyNodes

Semantic atoms (compressed kernels).

✔ NoveltyScore

A 0–1 score indicating conceptual novelty vs. Pantheon memory.

✔ DomainLinks

List of Pantheon Domains that should receive the Honey.

Example:

["Domain 3 — Narrative Tensor Engine", "Domain 11 — MIIL"]


⸻

⭐ 2.6 Doctrine Block

The Garden + Conductor synthesis layer.

Fields:

✔ Routes

Doctrines this artifact contributes to.

✔ Confidence

Probability that the artifact’s semantic content maps correctly.

✔ FrameDeltaContribution

What gets written to the continuity ledger.

Example:

{
  "NarrativeDelta": { "shift": "exploratory → architectural" },
  "IntentVector": [0.1, 0.9, 0.0],
  "ValueVector": [0.82],
  "BoundaryLayers": ["Artifact", "Silence"]
}


⸻

⭐ 2.7 Audit Block

Signed by:
	•	Mirror
	•	Hypatia
	•	Merkle Warden
	•	Sovereign Kernel

Ensures:
	•	authorization
	•	ethics
	•	provenance
	•	immutability

Example:

{
  "Verifier": "MerkleWarden",
  "Timestamp": "2025-11-30T18:44:02Z",
  "KernelSignature": "0xA7E3F..."
}


⸻

⭐ 3. Lifecycle Summary

Raw File
 → ArtifactSignature (Hound)
 → GeometryMap (Spider + Hypatia)
 → HoneyBundle (Bee + Dragonfly)
 → DoctrineRouting (Garden + Conductor)
 → FrameDeltaContribution (EchoFrame)
 → Raw file destroyed
 → Universal File Schema saved

This allows…
	•	complete safety
	•	deterministic replication
	•	perfect auditability
	•	cross-Pantheon portability
	•	compression-based emergence
	•	multi-modal cognition

